// Slavic gods × 12 — the pre-Christian pantheon of the Slavic world — SEO funnel.
// /gab44/slavic-gods (index) + /gab44/slavic-gods/{slug}.
//
// Eleventh great pantheon on gab44 after Olympians, Norse, Hindu, Egyptian, Celtic,
// Orishas, Mesopotamian, Aztec, Shinto, and Chinese. The pantheon of c. 250-300
// million ethnic Slavs across Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, Poland, Czech Republic,
// Slovakia, Bulgaria, Serbia, Croatia, Slovenia, North Macedonia, Bosnia, and the
// diaspora. The most-recently-suppressed of any major European pantheon — Vladimir
// the Great of Kievan Rus formally Christianized the Eastern Slavs in 988 CE,
// threw the Perun idol into the Dnieper river, and ordered the systematic
// destruction of all pagan shrines. The Western Slavs at Arkona on Rügen held
// out until 1168 CE when the Danish king Valdemar I destroyed the Svantevit
// temple. The Lithuanian-Slavic frontier was the last pagan polity in Europe to
// convert (1387 for Lithuania, 1413 for Samogitia). The pantheon whose primary
// written sources are *all hostile* — the Primary Chronicle by the Christian
// monk Nestor c. 1113, Helmold's Chronica Slavorum c. 1170, Saxo Grammaticus
// c. 1208, Adam of Bremen c. 1075, the Mater Verborum 13th c. — meaning every
// source-critical reading must reckon with the Christian framing. The pantheon
// most contested by contemporary nationalism: claimed simultaneously by Russian-
// Eurasianist state-ideology (Putin's "ancient Russian spirit"), Ukrainian
// Rodnovery as anti-Russian heritage of Kyivan Rus, Polish narodowo-katolicki
// extreme-right, Belarusian opposition cultural revival, and Western-occidentalist
// neopaganism. The pantheon whose Indo-European-comparative reconstruction (after
// Jakobson 1969 on Perun-Veles thunder-snake mytheme, Ivanov & Toporov 1974) is
// methodologically the most rigorous of any reconstructed pantheon — but whose
// 19th-c. Romantic-nationalist reconstructions (Hanka, Bielowski, Voskresensky)
// and 20th-c. forgeries (the Veles Book / Vlesova kniga, fabricated 1950s by
// Yury Mirolyubov) are still cited in popular Slavic-pagan literature.
//
// Three families × 4 gods:
//  - Sovereigns of Heaven & Order: Perun thunder-king of Vladimir's 980 pantheon;
//    Svarog the celestial blacksmith who forged the sun and sky; Dazhbog the
//    "wealth-giver" sun-god whose name appears in the Igor Tale as "grandfather
//    of the Russian people"; Stribog the wind-god, "grandfather of the eight
//    winds" in the Igor Tale.
//  - Earth, Hearth & Life: Mokosh the only female deity in Vladimir's 980
//    pantheon, weaver-of-fate and damp-earth-mother; Veles the earth-cattle-
//    poetry-magic-underworld god, Perun's eternal opposite in the Indo-European
//    thunder-snake mytheme; Lada the spring-love-marriage goddess of the
//    Western-Slavic folk-song refrains (and the most-contested member of the
//    pantheon — Brückner 1918 argued Lada is merely a folk-song exclamation,
//    never a real goddess; Gieysztor 1982 defended her authenticity); Yarilo
//    the dying-and-rising young god of spring fertility, ritually killed and
//    mourned at Kupala / midsummer.
//  - Threshold & Shadow: Morana (Marzanna, Marena) the winter-death goddess
//    ritually drowned-in-effigy every March equinox to end the winter; Chernobog
//    the "black god of misfortune" attested only by Helmold 1170; Belobog the
//    "white god of fortune" reconstructed as Chernobog's dyad-counterpart (almost
//    certainly a partial Helmold-Christian construction); Rod the primordial
//    creator-and-clan-ancestor whose name is the etymon of every Slavic word for
//    "kin, birth, nation" (rod, rodit', rodina, narod, priroda).
//
// Source-honest from: the *Povest' Vremennykh Let* (Повѣсть времѧньныхъ лѣтъ,
// Primary Chronicle, c. 1113 CE Nestor of Kyiv — Vladimir's 980 pantheon at
// Kyiv, the 988 destruction of the Perun idol, the Slavic-pagan oath-rituals);
// the *Slovo o polku Igoreve* (Слово о пълку Игоревѣ, Tale of Igor's Campaign,
// c. 1185-1187 — the only extant pre-Mongol East-Slavic epic, mentioning
// Stribog, Dazhbog "grandfather of the Russian people," Veles, and the Boyan
// "Veles' grandson" bard-tradition); Helmold of Bosau *Chronica Slavorum*
// (c. 1170 — the Black-God / Chernobog mention, the Western-Slavic deities of
// the Polabians); Saxo Grammaticus *Gesta Danorum* (c. 1208 — the Svantevit
// temple at Arkona on Rügen, destroyed by Valdemar I in 1168); Adam of Bremen
// *Gesta Hammaburgensis Ecclesiae Pontificum* (c. 1075 — the Slavic temples
// at Rethra and Wolin); Procopius *De Bello Gothico* (c. 6th c. CE — the
// Antes-and-Sclaveni worship of "one god, maker of lightning"); the *Mater
// Verborum* (13th c. Czech glossary — Czech Slavic deity names); Cosmas of
// Prague *Chronica Boemorum* (c. 1125 — Czech pagan survivals); the Kievan
// metropolitan Ilarion's *Slovo o zakone i blagodati* (c. 1050); the *Slovo
// nekoego khristolyubtsa* (12th c. — anti-pagan sermon listing Perun, Khors,
// Mokosh, Veles, vily-rusalki); the Igor Tale's reference to *Khors* (a deity
// of disputed Iranian-Khorz / Slavic-Hors origin); modern scholarship:
// Lubor Niederle *Slovanské starožitnosti* (1902-1934 — the foundational
// archaeology); Aleksander Brückner *Mitologia słowiańska* 1918, *Mitologia
// polska* 1924 (the great Polish skeptic-philologist who demolished many 19th-c.
// reconstructions); Roman Jakobson "The Slavic God Veles and his Indo-European
// Cognates" 1969 (the canonical Perun-Veles thunder-snake mytheme paper);
// Vyacheslav V. Ivanov & Vladimir N. Toporov *Issledovaniya v oblasti
// slavyanskikh drevnostey* 1974 (the foundational Russian structuralist
// reconstruction); Boris Rybakov *Yazichestvo Drevnikh Slavyan* 1981 and
// *Yazichestvo Drevney Rusi* 1987 (the great Soviet-era archaeologist —
// methodologically expansive, with parts contested); Aleksander Gieysztor
// *Mitologia Słowian* 1982 (the canonical Polish synthesis); Marija Gimbutas
// *The Slavs* 1971 (the kurgan-hypothesis Indo-European framework); Patrice
// Lajoye *Perun, dieu slave de l'orage* 2015 (the most-recent French
// Indo-European comparative); Mike Dixon-Kennedy *Encyclopedia of Russian and
// Slavic Myth and Legend* 1998; Joanne Asala *Polish Folklore and Myth* 2001;
// Mirjam Mencej *Styrian Witches in European Perspective* 2017 for the
// south-Slavic witch-and-vampire substrate.
//
// Shadow-honest about: the systematic 988-1387 Christianization, which destroyed
// the temple-and-idol layer of Slavic religion with unusual thoroughness (the
// 12th-c. Slavic Bible translations and Cyrillic-literacy push *replaced* rather
// than syncretized with the pagan substrate, unlike Greek/Roman/Celtic where
// church-and-pagan iconography fused); Vladimir the Great throwing the Perun
// idol into the Dnieper river in 988 (the canonical East-Slavic conversion-
// trauma) and the parallel Danish destruction of the Svantevit temple at Arkona
// 1168 (the West-Slavic equivalent); the 19th-c. Romantic-nationalist forgeries
// — Hanka's *Královédvorský rukopis* and *Zelenohorský rukopis* (1817-1819, the
// great Czech-revival forgeries debunked by Masaryk in the 1880s) and the
// Bielowski / Voskresensky Polish-Russian Romantic reconstructions; the
// Soviet-era *Vlesova kniga* / Veles Book (fabricated by Yury Mirolyubov in
// the 1950s in Brussels, claiming to be a 9th-c. wooden-tablet Slavic-pagan
// scripture — universally rejected by Slavists but still cited in Russian and
// Ukrainian Rodnovery literature); the contemporary Russian-Eurasianist state-
// ideological appropriation of "ancient Russian spirit" under Putin and Dugin;
// the Wagner Group's use of pagan-Slavic iconography (the Valknut adapted-into-
// Slavic-Kolovrat, the Perun-axe-tattoos on mercenaries); the Ukraine-Russia
// mythological-heritage dispute over Kyivan Rus (both states claim Vladimir's
// 988 baptism, with Russia framing it as proto-Russian and Ukraine framing it
// as proto-Ukrainian — a primary cultural-political fault-line of the 2022-
// ongoing war); the Polish far-right (Marsz Niepodległości, ONR) use of the
// Trzy Pióra / Kolovrat iconography; the Czech and Slovak Rodnoverí groups
// who oscillate between authentic-cultural-revival and white-nationalist
// adjacency; the Belarusian Iron Cross movement; the Russian Imperial Movement
// (Russkoye Imperskoye Dvizheniye) designated as terrorist by the US in 2020
// for using Slavic-pagan iconography to recruit; the Witcher / Sapkowski /
// CD Projekt Red dark-fantasy commodification of Slavic-folklore (Cthulhu-
// adjacent moral-relativist framing that flattens the pre-Christian register);
// the Marzanna-drowning festival modern revival as "cultural-not-religious"
// folk-craft event in Poland (which both preserves and de-fangs the death-
// goddess); the Lada-controversy (Brückner 1918 demonstrated that "Lada" in
// folk-songs is a meaningless refrain-exclamation, not a goddess name; Gieysztor
// 1982 partially restored her; the 21st-c. Rodnovery movement has fully
// re-canonized her without resolving the source-critical debate); the
// 19th-c. Jakob Grimm extraction of Slavic material into a "Germanic-Slavic
// proto-pagan" framework that flattened Slavic distinctiveness; the silent
// extraction of pagan-Slavic ritual into the Orthodox calendar (Perun's day
// → Saint Elijah / Ilya-Prorok July 20, the storm-saint who took over Perun's
// thunder-cult; Veles → Saint Blaise / Vlasiy February 11, the cattle-saint
// who took over Veles's livestock-cult; Mokosh → Saint Paraskeva-Pyatnitsa,
// the "Friday-saint" who took over Mokosh's weaving-and-fertility-cult);
// the 21st-c. Slavic-fantasy aesthetic commodification on TikTok and Instagram
// (Slavic-witch core, Perun-tattoo trend, Domovoy/house-spirit kitsch) without
// the source-critical or political-context register — named per deity where
// the connection is direct.

